  <h2>How do you spot unlicensed platforms?</h2>

  <p>Unlicensed platforms targeting Filipino players are not always obvious. Many invest heavily in professional-looking websites, social media marketing, and celebrity endorsements. The following six red flags, taken individually or in combination, should prompt serious skepticism.</p>

  <h3>Red flag 1: No PAGCOR license number displayed</h3>

  <p>Legitimate PAGCOR-licensed platforms display their license number prominently, typically in the footer of the website and in the "About" or "Legal" section. If you cannot find a PAGCOR license number anywhere on the platform &mdash; not in the terms and conditions, not on the homepage, not in the app settings &mdash; treat this as the most basic indicator that the platform may not be licensed.</p>

  <p>Some unlicensed platforms will display logos or badges that resemble PAGCOR certification without providing an actual license number. A badge without a verifiable number is meaningless.</p>

  <h3>Red flag 2: Claims foreign jurisdiction only</h3>

  <p>A platform that claims to be licensed by the Curacao Gaming Authority, Malta Gaming Authority, or Isle of Man Gambling Supervision Commission &mdash; without a corresponding PAGCOR license &mdash; is not authorized to serve Filipino players within the Philippines. Foreign licenses do not confer Philippine operating authority. Full stop.</p>

  <p>This is one of the most common deceptions. The platform is technically licensed somewhere, which gives it an air of legitimacy. But that license does not extend to the Philippine market, and it provides no recourse through Philippine regulatory channels.</p>

  <h3>Red flag 3: Cryptocurrency-only deposits</h3>

  <p>PAGCOR-licensed platforms are required to support Philippine peso transactions and typically offer GCash, Maya, bank transfers, and over-the-counter payment options. A platform that accepts only Bitcoin, USDT, or other cryptocurrencies and does not offer peso-denominated transactions is very likely not PAGCOR-licensed.</p>

  <p>Cryptocurrency is not inherently problematic, and some licensed platforms offer it as one of several payment options. The red flag is exclusivity &mdash; when crypto is the only way to deposit and withdraw, it typically means the platform is structured to avoid Philippine financial regulatory oversight.</p>

  <h3>Red flag 4: Guaranteed returns or fixed daily income</h3>

  <p>No legitimate gaming platform guarantees returns. Casino games are inherently probabilistic, and the house always has an edge. Any platform promising "guaranteed daily income," "fixed returns," or "investment-grade yields" through gaming is either a scam or structured as an unlicensed securities offering masquerading as a gaming platform.</p>

  <p>This red flag has been particularly prevalent in platforms targeting lower-income Filipino players, often promoted through Facebook groups and TikTok. The PAGCOR Player Protection Office issued a specific advisory in February 2026 warning against platforms using "guaranteed income" language.</p>

  <h3>Red flag 5: Aggressive recruitment or MLM-style referrals</h3>

  <p>PAGCOR-licensed platforms may offer referral bonuses, but they do not operate multi-level marketing structures. If a platform's primary recruitment mechanism involves recruiting other players for tiered commissions &mdash; where your earnings depend more on sign-ups than on actual gaming &mdash; this is a hallmark of a pyramid structure, not a licensed gaming operation.</p>

  <h3>Red flag 6: Unusual domain extensions</h3>

  <p>While not definitive on its own, platforms operating on domains with extensions like .xyz, .vip, .fun, .top, or .click should receive additional scrutiny. Most PAGCOR-licensed platforms use .com, .ph, or .com.ph domains. Unusual extensions are frequently associated with platforms that expect to be shut down and relaunched under new domains &mdash; a pattern inconsistent with legitimate, licensed operations.</p>

