  <h2>What should you do if something goes wrong?</h2>

  <p>Even on licensed platforms, disputes happen. Withdrawals can be delayed. Bonus terms can be misunderstood. Technical glitches can affect game outcomes. Knowing the complaint process before you need it is part of responsible gaming.</p>

  <h3>Step 1: Document everything</h3>

  <p>Before contacting anyone, gather your evidence. Take screenshots of the issue: the transaction in question, the game round, the bonus terms, any chat transcripts with customer support. Note the date, time, amounts involved, and your account ID. The more documentation you have, the stronger your case.</p>

  <h3>Step 2: Use the platform's internal complaint process</h3>

  <p>Every PAGCOR-licensed operator is required to have an internal complaint resolution process. Start here. Contact customer support through the platform's official channels (not social media) and file a formal complaint. Ask for a case reference number and a timeline for resolution. Most platforms are required to acknowledge complaints within 48 hours and resolve them within 15 business days.</p>

  <h3>Step 3: Escalate to PAGCOR's Player Protection Office</h3>

  <p>If the platform does not resolve your complaint within 15 business days, or if the resolution is unsatisfactory, you can escalate to PAGCOR. Send a formal complaint to <strong>playerprotection@pagcor.ph</strong> with the following information:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Your full name and contact details</li>
    <li>The platform name and your account ID</li>
    <li>A clear description of the issue</li>
    <li>All supporting documentation (screenshots, transaction records, chat logs)</li>
    <li>Your case reference number from the platform's internal process</li>
    <li>The date you filed the internal complaint and the platform's response (or lack thereof)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>PAGCOR reviews complaints and can compel licensed operators to take corrective action, including releasing frozen funds, correcting erroneous game outcomes, or clarifying bonus terms. In serious cases, PAGCOR can impose fines or suspend an operator's license.</p>

  <h3>Step 4: If still unresolved, escalate to the PAGCOR Board</h3>

  <p>For complaints that remain unresolved after the Player Protection Office review, you can escalate to the PAGCOR Board of Directors through the Office of the Chairman. This is the final regulatory escalation step. Beyond this, your options are legal action through the Philippine courts or a complaint to the Department of Justice.</p>

