  <p>PAGCOR's self-exclusion program allows you to request a voluntary ban from all PAGCOR-licensed platforms. Once activated, licensed operators are required to close your account and refuse future registrations. The exclusion can be set for 6 months, 1 year, or indefinitely. Contact PAGCOR's Player Protection Office or request self-exclusion through any licensed platform's responsible gambling settings.</p>

  <div class="key-takeaway">
    <h4>Key Takeaway</h4>
    <ul>
      <li>Always verify a PAGCOR license before depositing money &mdash; use at least two of the three methods described above</li>
      <li>GCash integration is a useful secondary signal but is not a substitute for license verification</li>
      <li>Six red flags can help you identify unlicensed platforms before you lose money</li>
      <li>Know the complaint process before you need it: document, internal complaint, PAGCOR escalation</li>
      <li>If gambling is causing problems, PAGCOR's self-exclusion program and the National Mental Health Crisis Hotline (1553) are available 24/7</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
  <div class="faq-section">
    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How do I check if an online casino is PAGCOR-licensed?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">There are three methods: (1) Visit the official PAGCOR website at pagcor.ph and search the licensee registry. (2) Check the license number format &mdash; legitimate licenses follow the pattern eGames-YYYY-NNN or PIGO-YYYY-NNN. (3) Contact PAGCOR directly at licensing@pagcor.ph or their Player Protection Office hotline to verify a specific operator. Use at least two methods before depositing money on any platform.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What protections does a PAGCOR license give players?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">A PAGCOR license provides five key protections: background checks on operators, RNG (Random Number Generator) testing for game fairness, segregated player funds so your deposits are separate from the company's operating money, anti-money laundering compliance, and a formal complaint channel through PAGCOR's Player Protection Office. It does not guarantee winnings, good customer service, or fair bonus terms.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What are the red flags for unlicensed online casinos in the Philippines?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Six major red flags: (1) No PAGCOR license number displayed on the platform. (2) Claims to be licensed only in a foreign jurisdiction like Curacao or Malta without a PAGCOR license. (3) Accepts only cryptocurrency with no GCash or bank transfer option. (4) Promises guaranteed returns or daily fixed income. (5) Relies on aggressive social media recruitment or MLM-style referral programs. (6) Uses unusual domain extensions like .xyz, .vip, or .fun. Any one of these warrants caution; multiple red flags together are a strong warning.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Is GCash integration a sign of a legitimate PAGCOR-licensed casino?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">GCash is currently integrated with 47 of approximately 50 PAGCOR-licensed platforms (94%). While GCash integration alone does not guarantee legitimacy, its absence on a platform claiming to serve Filipino players is a significant yellow flag. GCash conducts its own due diligence on gaming partners, so integration serves as a secondary verification layer beyond PAGCOR licensing itself.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How do I file a complaint against a PAGCOR-licensed operator?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">First, document the issue with screenshots, transaction IDs, and dates. Then file a formal complaint through the platform's internal process and request a case reference number. If the platform does not resolve the complaint within 15 business days, escalate to PAGCOR's Player Protection Office at playerprotection@pagcor.ph with all supporting documentation. If still unresolved, escalate to the PAGCOR Board through the Office of the Chairman.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the difference between e-Games and PIGO licensed casinos?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Both are PAGCOR-administered licenses for online gaming in the Philippines. e-Games licenses (approximately 38 active) focus on electronic gaming, slots, and virtual tables with PHP 25 million minimum capital. PIGO licenses (approximately 12 active) cover full-suite gaming including sports betting with PHP 100 million minimum capital. From a player protection standpoint, both provide PAGCOR oversight, though PIGO operators face stricter anti-money laundering and identity verification requirements.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Can I play on offshore-licensed online casinos from the Philippines?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Playing on platforms not licensed by PAGCOR is technically illegal for Filipino players under Philippine law. Offshore-licensed casinos holding only Curacao, Malta, or other foreign licenses are not authorized to accept wagers from players physically located in the Philippines. While enforcement against individual players has been minimal, these platforms offer no recourse through Philippine regulatory channels if disputes arise, your funds are frozen, or the platform shuts down.</div>
    </div>
